{
  "text": "Chronic hibernating myocardium also retains the ability to transiently increase function in response to ␤-adrenergic stimulation, despite a critical limitation in coronary flow reserve, but the metabolic consequences of this are unknown. Although functional changes after graded increases in demand are blunted because of the inability of subendocardial flow to increase, regional wall motion does not deteriorate. [CITATION_1] These findings could be due to intrinsic cellular adaptations induced in hibernating myocardium that downregulate regional energy utilization to prevent the development of metabolic ischemia. Thus, a downregulation of resting flow and function could allow the myocardium to respond to modest increases in the external determinants of workload without the immediate development of metabolic evidence of ischemia. This could conceivably minimize periods of repetitive acute supply-demand imbalance that lead to acute myocardial stunning.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "32688277"
